items.title: Earthquake triggers 'slow motion' quakes in New Zealand
items.summary: Slow slip events, a type of slow motion earthquake that occurs over days to weeks, are thought to be capable of triggering larger, potentially damaging earthquakes. In a new study, scientists have documented the first clear-cut instance of the reverse -- a massive earthquake immediately triggering a series of large slow slip events.

items.title: Muscle nuclei: May the force be with you
items.summary: A group of researchers has revealed the mechanism by which cellular nuclei reach their position within muscle cells. This discovery can have important implications in therapeutic strategies to treat muscular diseases.

items.title: Later circadian timing of food intake is associated with increased body mass index
items.summary: Investigators examine the relationships between body fat and body mass index, and the timing of food consumption, to time of day and to the body's circadian or body clock.
